 Nogais, Russians, Ukrainians, and other groups transformed their environments and adapted to life in the Molochna Valley.Staples contends that the allocation and use of land formed a central hub around which public life in Molochna revolved, and determined the success or failure of each group. Ultimately, he concludes, it was the settlers, not the state, who decided how they would adapt to the arid southern Ukrainian steppe. Perhaps most importantly, Staples makes a major contribution to the investigation of how peasant groups can emerge from their traditionalist mentality and life-style as the Mennonites of Molochna did. His thoughtful analysis will be a welcome addition to the study of both Tsarist peasant history and Russian and Ukrainian agricultural and peasant history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aLand settlementxGovernment policyzRussiaxHistory. 0aLand settlementzUkrainezMolochansḱ RegionvCross-cultural studies. 0aLand settlementzUkrainezMolochansḱ RegionvCross-cultural studies. 0aSteppeszUkrainezMolochna River RegionxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Russia & the Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831104909540 cprintz978080203724440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144267362540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442673625423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781442673625/original  a978-3-11-049095-4  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK